ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-10T161153.475.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260429T065159Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credit: M. Palani Kumar\nA portfolio review session led by photographer and journalist M. Palani Kumar\, founder of the People’s Photographers Archive\, whose work documents the lives of working-class women and marginalized communities. The session offers an opportunity to explore how personal stories can be situated within broader societal narratives through visual practice\, while engaging with the idea of “witness” in long-term documentary work. Drawing on projects spanning 8–9 years\, it reflects on themes of caste violence\, forced evictions\, and environmental degradation\, examining their impact on both ecology and the communities that depend on it. \n\nParticipants are invited to present portfolios that engage with caste- and lineage-based narratives as lived experiences\, and to consider how to document working-class lives\, gender\, and labour with sensitivity and accountability. Emphasizing ethical representation and storytelling from within communities\, the session foregrounds the importance of centering and amplifying voices that are often marginalized or unheard. \n\nPlease submit your portfolio on the form by May 10\, 2026 9pm IST. \n\nThis event is part of programming around Beneath the Turning Sky in collaboration with People's Archives of Rural India (PARI)
DTEND:20260516T110000Z
DTSTART:20260516T080000Z
SUMMARY:Image as Witness: Portfolio Review with Palani Kumar
UID:1262@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/image-as-witness-portfolio-review-with-palani-kumar-2/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-22T111926.220.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260422T055011Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a guided walkthrough of the Living Botanicals installation in the MAP’s Sculpture courtyard led by its grower Kush Sethi. Kush is a gardener and a forager from Delhi who has helped us create a living and breathing space\, in collaboration with Architect Bhavana La Noche. In May\, he returns to engage our audiences with gardening and walkthroughs of the plants in this installation.\n\nCome along to hear tales behind this garden’s inception\, behind-the-scenes and stories of plants from Hortus Malabaricus to Bangalore. Spend time in this living ecosystem observing plants from the lens of an explorer. We have also provided a field kit of assorted lenses which will allow you to zoom into the ecology of this garden. Bring a diary to draw\, press things and take notes.
DTEND:20260509T061500Z
DTSTART:20260509T053000Z
SUMMARY:Living Botanicals
UID:1258@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/living-botanicals-3/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-01T161439.576.png
CATEGORIES:Kids & Family,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260406T093857Z
DESCRIPTION:Spend the summer inside a museum\, learning from professional artists. Our workshops for children aged 8–12 are hands-on\, creative\, and fun\, covering everything from tie-dye to ceramics and more. \n\nChoose your experience\n\nRegister for individual workshops\, or go all-in with our combination ticket for access to every session throughout the camp.\n\nMay 4\n\nCeramics and Mask Making Workshop\n\nMay 5\n\nAnthotype and Cyanotype Workshop\n\nMay 6\n\nCanvas City\n\nMay 7\n\nGrowing From Nothing: A Gardening Walk Workshop\n\nMay 8\n\nNatural Tie-Dye Workshop\n\nEnd-of-camp showcase\n\nThe final day is a celebration where the participants present everything they made over the summer\, open for all families to attend.\n\nNote: \n\n-Please pack a lunch\, snacks\, and a water bottle for your child each day.\n\n-Every registered participant receives a gift store voucher of equal value\, redeemable at the MAP Gift Store. \n\n-If you're a working parent\, our café space is open for you to use while your child is in session.\n\nThese workshops are for children between the ages of 8-12. If you are between the ages of 13-16 check out our programme here.\n\nSpots are limited. Register early to secure your place.
DTEND:20260509T103000Z
DTSTART:20260504T043000Z
SUMMARY:Summer at MAP (Ages 8-12)
UID:1239@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/summer-at-map-ages-8-12/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Vishal_Kumaraswamy_Marana_02.jpg
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260508T130424Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Vishal Kumaraswamy/Marana\nIn this talk\, we hear from Vishal Kumaraswamy\, an artist-curator about his practices and projects. Stemming from anti-caste working principles\, his practice brings together traditional and experimental forms to investigate the entanglements of body\, caste\, language\, technology\, and society. He is interested in the power and potential of media technologies to imagine embodied\, gestural ways of fostering the further development of Dalit cultural practices.\n\nCentral to their inquiry is the continuity of Dalit ritualistic and cultural practices\, Marana (on funeral processions) and how these embodied performances are impacted by shifting urban spaces and technological intervention. Kumaraswamy investigates how technology can be repurposed to document and sustain these legacies rather than erase them. He creates space for new\, collaborative modes of representation that challenge dominant urban narratives.\n\nThe event is presented as part of a monthly series that brings in artists and artistic practices rooted in Bengaluru\, developed in collaboration with Ananya Drishya.
DTEND:20260515T133000Z
DTSTART:20260515T123000Z
SUMMARY:Towards a New Commons: Technology\, Media and Dalit Cultural Practices
UID:1271@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/towards-a-new-commons-technology-media-and-dalit-cultural-practices/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/The-Heat-is-On-Climate-Change-and-its-Impact-on-Womens-Mental-HealthSanskriti-Talwar.jpg
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260505T035150Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Sanskriti Talwar\nThis talk looks at how changing weather\, excessive heat\, floods and more are causing mental distress to agricultural workers. Older women\, already burdened by age-related health issues\, are finding it harder  to cope. The burden on women is disproportionately higher—fetching firewood and water takes more time and energy as summers arrive earlier\, last longer and are hotter than before. Cooking on burning fires adds to their overall heat stress\, often a job they do outside the home as well.\n\nThis event is part of programming around Beneath the Turning Sky in collaboration with People’s Archives of Rural India (PARI)
DTEND:20260517T130000Z
DTSTART:20260517T120000Z
SUMMARY:Climate Change and its Impact on Women’s Mental Health
UID:1267@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/climate-change-and-its-impact-on-womens-mental-health/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-02T112617.763.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260408T045758Z
DESCRIPTION:Five days\, a museum full of inspiration\, and a workshop unlike any other\, join film maker Hansa Thapliyal for doll-making and stop-motion animation at MAP.\n\nUsing the museum as a creative playground\, participants will work with everyday materials and scraps to build their own dolls\, drawing inspiration from our exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky. Along the way\, they'll explore their ideas\, experiment with storytelling\, and find their own creative voice.\n\nThrough playful stop-motion exercises\, these ideas will begin to move\, building into a collaborative animated film screened at the end of Summer at MAP.\n\nParticipants are required to bring:\n\n-A mobile phone with a camera\n\n-A few discarded items from home to add a personal touch to the creations\n\nNote: \n\n-Please pack a lunch\, snacks\, and a water bottle for your child each day.\n\n-Every registered participant receives a gift store voucher of equal value\, redeemable at the MAP Gift Store. \n\n-If you're a working parent\, our café space is open for you to use while your child is in session.\n\nThese workshops are for children between the ages of 13-16 If you are between the ages of 8-12 check out our programme here.\n\nSpots are limited. Register early to secure your place.
DTEND:20260516T103000Z
DTSTART:20260511T043000Z
SUMMARY:Summer at MAP (Ages 13-16)
UID:1240@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/summer-at-map-ages-13-16/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-1.png
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260507T054349Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a photo talk that journeys through the lives of nomadic pastoral communities whose movement\, labour\, and knowledge have long shaped the ecologies of the Indian subcontinent – across mountains\, deserts\, forests and more. Presented as part of the public programming for Beneath the Turning Sky\, and in collaboration with People’s Archive of Rural India (PARI)\, this session reflects on pastoralism as both livelihood and way of life—deeply attuned to seasons\, landscapes\, and the needs of livestock. .\n\nThrough photographs and conversation\, the talk will trace the lives of the Changpas of Ladakh and the Fakirani Jats of Kachchh—communities navigating fragile ecosystems while facing mounting pressures from climate change\, industrial expansion\, and displacement. Bringing together image-making and oral histories\, the session invites audiences to consider migration\, resilience\, and the futures of communities whose histories are often overlooked. \n\nThis event is part of programming around Beneath the Turning Sky in collaboration with People’s Archives of Rural India (PARI)
DTEND:20260516T130000Z
DTSTART:20260516T120000Z
SUMMARY:Photo Talk: Land\, Livelihood\, and Loss
UID:1264@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/photo-talk-land-livelihood-and-loss/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Songs-of-Labour-Living-Archives-Sinchita-Majhi.jpg
CATEGORIES:Listening Session,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260505T034741Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Songs of Labour-Living Archives-Sinchita Majhi\nJoin us for a special listening session around the Grindmill Songs Projectand Songs of the Rann\, by the People's Archive of Rural India (PARI)\, which brings together sound\, memory\, and conversation. Facilitated by Namita Waikar and Pratishtha\, this session explores songs as intimate emotional archives—voices that carry lived histories of women’s labour\, resilience\, longing\, humour\, and dissent. \n\nSung while performing everyday work\, these songs reveal how labour\, caste\, gender\, and patriarchy are woven into daily life\, while also creating spaces of expression and solidarity. Through collective listening and discussion\, we will reflect on the power of oral traditions and informal cultural transmission in preserving stories and sustaining memory across generations.\n\n\n\nThis event is part of programming around Beneath the Turning Sky in collaboration with People’s Archives of Rural India (PARI)\n\n\n\n
DTEND:20260516T073000Z
DTSTART:20260516T053000Z
SUMMARY:Songs of Labour: Living Archives
UID:1261@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/songs-of-labour-living-archives/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-5.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260505T035012Z
DESCRIPTION:Ethics of Documenting Labour-Rahul Maganti\nWhat constitutes labour — and who gets to define it? Labour takes many forms\, yet documentation has long been shaped by those with the privilege to record\, which means it has also long been shaped by what they choose to overlook. The everyday work of women in the home\, the intricate skill behind craft processes\, the invisible hands in agriculture\, these rarely make it into the frame.\nHow do we gather information that doesn't default to the most visible\, the most legible\, the most convenient?\nCaste is perhaps the sharpest example of this blind spot. The labour it assigns is among the most physically demanding and socially stigmatising\, and yet it remains among the most systematically erased from memory\, archive\, and public acknowledgement.\nTo truly account for labour is to reckon with who has been seen\, and who has been made invisible\, and by whom.\nThis event is part of programming around Beneath the Turning Sky in collaboration with People’s Archives of Rural India (PARI)
DTEND:20260517T083000Z
DTSTART:20260517T053000Z
SUMMARY:Ethics of Documenting Labour
UID:1265@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/ethics-of-documenting-labour/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Website-cover-images-new-6.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260508T055156Z
DESCRIPTION:Conceptualised and facilitated by Srivatsan Sankaran\, this session encourages participants to engage with Living Botanicals through photographic observation and image-based storytelling. As participants move through the space\, they will reflect on how movement\, body language\, and silent expression can be translated into compelling visual narratives\, resonating deeply with sign language and Deaf visual culture.\n\nThe session also introduces perspectives on how photography and AI can interact with visual languages\, opening new possibilities for documenting gestures\, expressions\, and moments of connection. Through the process of photographing and interpreting the space\, participants will experiment with telling stories through images inspired by the environment and their own expressions.\n\nBy combining a guided photo walk with collaborative visual exploration\, the workshop creates a space for participants to interpret gesture\, communication\, and space through their own visual narratives.
DTEND:20260530T110000Z
DTSTART:20260530T090000Z
SUMMARY:Framing Living Spaces: Visual Storytelling Through Photography & AI
UID:1269@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/framing-living-spaces-visual-storytelling-through-photography-ai/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-01T155341.726.png
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260406
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260509
CATEGORIES:Series,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260410T023206Z
DESCRIPTION:A series of faculty-led sessions in the form of talks\, lectures or workshops are delivered by faculty members of Srishti Manipal Institute of Art\, Design &amp\; Technology. These sessions range from sounds\, urban biodiversity\, metaphor-making\, livelihoods\, ecosystems and more.\n\nSchedule\nApril 7\nOn Seeing the Sound in a Changing Environment by Dr Guruaja\, K. V.\n\nApril 18\nWhere Have all the Sparrows Gone? by Aparna Raman\n\nApril 21\nSlow Disturbances by Priya Joseph\n\nApril 25\nClimate Metaphors by Asmita Sarkar\n\nMay 5\nThe Ghosts of Conservation by Rustam Vania\n\nMay 9\nClimate Canvases by Dr Chandrima Home and Dr Sambita Modak\n\nPlease note: Each session requires individual registration. Some sessions require you to bring certain materials so please be prepared.
SUMMARY:Learning Lounge
UID:1238@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/learning-lounge/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/1440-X-810-Widget-01.jpg
CATEGORIES:Film Screenings,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260430T050423Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a screening of documentary films by People's Archive of Rural India (PARI) that bring into focus the intertwined realities of climate change\, gender\, and labour across rural India. Through intimate and powerful storytelling\, these films trace how shifting ecologies reshape livelihoods\, deepen existing inequalities\, and place disproportionate burdens on women and marginalised communities. \n\nFrom farms and forests to coastlines and homes\, the screenings reveal stories of resilience\, adaptation\, and collective action in the face of environmental change. This programme invites audiences to reflect on climate justice not as an abstract future concern\, but as a lived present shaped by work\, care\, and survival.\n\n\n\nThis event is part of programming around Beneath the Turning Sky in collaboration with People’s Archives of Rural India (PARI)\n\n\n\n
DTEND:20260517T103000Z
DTSTART:20260517T093000Z
SUMMARY:Changing Landscapes: Films on Climate\, Gender & Labour
UID:1266@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/changing-landscapes-films-on-climate-gender-labour-2/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/DSC01571-scaled-e1778244988634.jpg
CATEGORIES:Drop-in Sessions,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260508T125725Z
DESCRIPTION:What does stitching mean to you? Is it an act of creation\, a therapeutic process\, or simply a fun activity? Either way\, drop in for a relaxed stitching session where you layer your thoughts into the process and create a souvenir to take home.\n\nMake @ MAP is a series that allows you to explore our collection in an engaging and hands-on manner. These sessions allow you to create and take home a special souvenir of your visit. It is perfect for all ages — so bring your friends and family and get ready to make some art! No experience is necessary\, just a willingness to have fun and experiment with new materials.
DTEND:20260531T093000Z
DTSTART:20260531T053000Z
SUMMARY:Make at MAP
UID:1270@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/make-at-map-8/
END:VEVENT
